column4: I just upgraded to 11.10, and when I try to install Wine, "apt-get install wine" gives me the error message "The following packages have unmet dependencies: wine : Depends: wine1.3 but it is not going to be installed. Depends: ia32-libs (>= 1.6) but it is not going to be installed. E: Unable to correct problems, you have held broken packages." Trying to install ia32-libs only complains that ia32-libs-multiarch isn't installed, etc.
you have no idea why?
I might have aborted some package updates because the computer froze
run « sudo dpkg --configure -a »
And then what? Nothing happens.
« sudo apt-get install -f »
that doesn't help, either
pastebin full output
http://pastebin.com/EJuKXNz1
run « sudo apt-get update » and try again.  If output is the same, pastebin the contents of /etc/apt/sources.list* and the output of the command « apt-cache policy wine wine1.3 ia32-libs »
sources.list here http://pastebin.com/m70XxPLZ and apt-cache here http://pastebin.com/N4eSW22v
why do you have precise repositories?
eh... I don't know.
How/where do I change them?
have you installed anything from precise?
not on purpose, no
doesn't matter if it was on purpose

if a significant portion of your system is on precise and you'd prefer to stay on natty, then you should just reinstall.  If you just added these repositories but never installed anything from them, then just remove them from your sources.list and run an « apt-get update »
I understand. To my knowledge I haven't, no
I see. Is there some easy way of seeing if it is? If a large portion is on precise, I mean
you could construct an aptitude search to do so, but I'd have to read the documentation to be more exact.  You can check individual packages just using apt-cache policy
okay, I will do that. Thanks for your help.
